,"Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Angus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Scottish Gaelic name  <b>Aonghas</b>  . Though still having a Scottish flavour, it has been used increasingly in modern times also by people without Scottish connections."],"variants":[{"name":"Aengus","meanings":["Usual Irish form of <b>Angus</b> ."]},{"name":"Aonghas","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>een</b>-yis’; from Celtic words meaning ‘one’ and ‘choice’. This is the name of an ancient Celtic god, and is first recorded as a personal name in Adomnan's ‘Life of St Columba’, where it occurs in the form <i>Oinogus(s)ius</i> as the name of a man for whom the saint prophesied a long life and a peaceful death. This is also almost certainly the name of the 8th-century Pictish king variously recorded as <i>Onnust</i> and <i>Hungus</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Angus de Atholia Third Laird of Glenerochie was born in 1180, in Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Henry de Atholia Third Earl of Atholia, was 22 and his mother, Margaret Comyn Countess Of Atholl, was 14. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with daughter of FitzEwen de Atholia. He died in 1240, in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1180–1240":"1180–1240","1190–1236":"1190–1236","1196–1244":"1196–1244","1200–1240":"1200–1240","–1268":"–1268","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1255–1355":"1255–1355","1270–1355":"1270–1355","1158–1211":"1158–1211","1166–1232":"1166–1232","1190":"11